It feels like that for me. I'm not even sure why I try. As a beginner furry artist you have to somehow make your drawings more realistic in proportion and more cartoony in expression at the same time, wtf? I wasn't built to think around corners like that.

Everyone you ask tells you different and conflicting advice, and the scope of your weaknesses is overwhelming. Somehow after all of that still feels like nobody has explained shit to you.

There's a pattern among most of the best artists; most started doodling in their free time, in notebooks that only they would see, without fear of judgement. They were also kids when they began, so they weren't old enough to judge themselves and their artistry.

Now, learning as an adult, you can be 'productive' drawing for an hour or two each day and still feel like a total fucking failure half the time. Most people would benefit from loving the process of drawing instead of the result. Part of me is convinced that I don’t like either.
